    <string name="troubleshoot_step_service_check">Service Check</string>
    <string name="troubleshoot_has_service_desc">Found service exposing AppFunctionService.</string>
    <string name="troubleshoot_no_service_desc">We couldn\'t find any service in your app that handles AppFunctions.\n\nTo fix this, make sure you have:\n1. Added the Jetpack AppFunction library to your dependencies.\n2. Declared a service in your AndroidManifest.xml with an intent-filter for \'android.app.appfunctions.AppFunctionService\'.\n3. Set the service to be exported (android:exported=\"true\").</string>
    <string name="troubleshoot_step_property_check">Property Check</string>
    <string name="troubleshoot_has_property_desc">Found \'android.app.appfunctions.v2\' property.</string>
    <string name="troubleshoot_no_property_desc">Your AppFunctionService is missing the required metadata property.\n\nTo fix this, add a &lt;property&gt; tag inside your &lt;service&gt; declaration in the manifest:\n&lt;property android:name=\"android.app.appfunctions.v2\" android:value=\"your_metadata_file.xml\" /&gt;\n\nThe value should point to the file in your assets folder containing the AppFunction metadata.</string>
    <string name="troubleshoot_step_asset_check">Asset Check</string>
    <string name="troubleshoot_has_asset_desc">Found metadata file in assets.</string>
    <string name="troubleshoot_no_asset_desc">The metadata file \'%1$s\' specified in your manifest property was not found in the app\'s assets.\n\nThis usually means the AppFunction compiler isn\'t set up correctly.\nTo fix this, please check:\n1. Did you add the AppFunction compiler as a KSP dependency?\n2. Did you set the KSP option \'appfunctions:aggregateAppFunctions\' to \'true\'?\n\nPlease refer to the AppFunction integration guideline to make sure the compiler is set up correctly.</string>
